% =============================================================================
\chapter{Stage 1: Finding and Critiquing a Dataset}
% =============================================================================

\section{Dataset Selection}

For this coursework I selected the \textbf{IMDb Non-Commercial Dataset}, freely published
at \url{https://datasets.imdbws.com/} and updated on a weekly basis by the Internet Movie
Database (IMDb). IMDb is the world's most authoritative source of film and television
metadata, collecting data from millions of users across the globe.

The dataset is distributed as a collection of tab-separated value (TSV) files compressed
with GNU Zip. For this project I used the following four files:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{IMDb TSV Files Used in This Project}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l l X}
  \toprule
  \textbf{File} & \textbf{Size (compressed)} & \textbf{Contents} \\
  \midrule
  \texttt{title.basics.tsv.gz}      & $\approx$135 MB & Core title metadata: title, type, year, runtime, genres \\
  \texttt{title.ratings.tsv.gz}     & $\approx$7 MB   & Aggregate user ratings and vote counts \\
  \texttt{title.principals.tsv.gz}  & $\approx$365 MB & Title--person associations (crew \& cast credits) \\
  \texttt{name.basics.tsv.gz}       & $\approx$200 MB & Person metadata: name, birth year, known professions \\
  \bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\label{tab:imdb-files}
\end{table}

To keep the local database manageable while still offering meaningful analysis,
I filtered the raw data during the import process to include \textbf{feature films
(\texttt{titleType = 'movie'}) released between 2000 and 2023 inclusive}.

