\section{Dataset Critique and Assessment}

The dataset was assessed against the six module criteria:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Dataset Assessment Against Module Criteria}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l X l}
  \toprule
  \textbf{Criterion} & \textbf{Assessment} & \textbf{Score} \\
  \midrule
  \textbf{Quality}
    & The data is curated and maintained directly by IMDb. Every title, rating, and credit
      is sourced from official IMDb records updated weekly.
      Null values are encoded using the explicit \texttt{\textbackslash{}N} convention
      rather than empty strings, making them machine-readable and easy to handle.
    & Excellent \\[0.6em]
  \textbf{Level of Detail}
    & Each title record carries runtime, year, adult classification, and up to three genre
      tags. Ratings carry both the average score and the total vote count, enabling
      statistical weighting. The \texttt{principal} table stores the exact job category
      of every credited crew member.
    & Very High \\[0.6em]
  \textbf{Documentation}
    & A comprehensive public data dictionary is available at
      \url{https://developer.imdb.com/non-commercial-datasets/}, specifying column names,
      types, null encoding, and update cadence for every file.
    & Excellent \\[0.6em]
  \textbf{Interrelation}
    & The four files form a natural relational graph: titles link to ratings via
      \texttt{tconst}; titles link to people via \texttt{title.principals.tsv} using
      both \texttt{tconst} and \texttt{nconst}. This multi-file structure inherently
      justifies a normalised relational database over flat-file storage.
    & High \\[0.6em]
  \textbf{Discoverability}
    & Files are publicly indexed at \url{https://datasets.imdbws.com/} with no account
      required. URLs are stable and directly downloadable.
    & Excellent \\[0.6em]
  \textbf{Terms of Use}
    & The dataset is licensed under the IMDb Non-Commercial Use terms (effectively
      CC BY-NC 4.0). Academic, non-commercial use is explicitly permitted.
    & Appropriate \\
  \bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\label{tab:assessment}
\end{table}

\section{Research Questions}

The richness of the IMDb dataset allows for meaningful multi-table analysis.
The following five research questions were formulated to guide the database design
and drive the web application:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, label=\textbf{RQ\arabic*.}]
  \item \textbf{Top Genres by Rating} ---
        Which film genres consistently earn the highest average IMDb ratings
        from viewers (considering genres with at least 50 rated titles)?

  \item \textbf{Top Directors by Average Rating} ---
        Who are the top 10 directors by average film rating, among those
        who have directed at least 5 rated feature films?

  \item \textbf{Rating Trends Over Time} ---
        How has the average movie rating evolved year-by-year from 2000 to 2023?
        Is there a discernible trend?

  \item \textbf{Runtime by Genre} ---
        Which film genres produce the longest movies on average?
        How do minimum and maximum runtimes vary by genre?

  \item \textbf{Versatile Directors} ---
        Which directors have worked across the greatest diversity of film genres
        throughout their careers (having directed at least 3 films)?
\end{enumerate}

Each question is answered with a specific parameterised SQL query, visualised with
an interactive Chart.js chart, and presented with a filterable data table in the
web application.

% =============================================================================
\chapter{Stage 2: Data Modelling}
% =============================================================================

\section{Conceptual Model --- Entity-Relationship Diagram}

The conceptual design identifies five core entities and their relationships:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Title} --- A feature film (the central entity).
  \item \textbf{Genre} --- A category of cinema (e.g., Drama, Comedy).
  \item \textbf{Rating} --- The aggregate user score for a title.
  \item \textbf{Person} --- A human credited on one or more titles.
  \item \textbf{Principal} --- The specific role a person played on a title.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.92\textwidth]{screenshots/er-diagram.png}
\caption{Entity--Relationship Diagram using Chen notation (rectangles for entities, ellipses for attributes, diamonds for relationships).}
\label{fig:er}
\end{figure}

\section{Relationships and Cardinalities}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Entity Relationships and Cardinalities}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l l l X}
  \toprule
  \textbf{Entity A} & \textbf{Cardinality} & \textbf{Entity B} & \textbf{Resolution} \\
  \midrule
  Title & 1:1 & Rating &
    A title may have zero or one rating; a rating belongs to exactly one title.
    Stored as a separate table with a FK, allowing unrated titles to exist. \\[0.4em]
  Title & M:N & Genre &
    A title can belong to many genres (e.g., ``Drama, Thriller''); a genre
    encompasses many titles. Resolved via the \texttt{title\_genre} junction table. \\[0.4em]
  Title & M:N & Person &
    A title involves many people in different roles; a person may work on many
    titles. Resolved via the \texttt{principal} junction table, which additionally
    stores the \texttt{category} (e.g., ``director'') and \texttt{job} attributes
    of the participation. \\
  \bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\label{tab:cardinalities}
\end{table}

\section{Normalisation Analysis}

The schema was designed from the outset to satisfy the \textbf{Third Normal Form (3NF)}.
The reasoning for each step is presented below.

\subsection{First Normal Form (1NF)}

A relation is in 1NF when all attributes contain only \textit{atomic} (indivisible)
values and there are no repeating groups.

\textbf{Problem in raw IMDb data:} The \texttt{title.basics.tsv} file stores genres as
a comma-separated string in a single column, e.g.\
\texttt{"Comedy,Drama,Romance"}. This is a multi-valued, non-atomic attribute ---
a direct violation of 1NF.

\textbf{Solution applied:} Genres are extracted into a dedicated \texttt{genre}
lookup table (one row per genre name) and linked to titles via the
\texttt{title\_genre} junction table. Every attribute across all six tables now
holds a single atomic value.

\subsection{Second Normal Form (2NF)}

A relation is in 2NF when it is in 1NF \emph{and} every non-key attribute is
\textit{fully functionally dependent} on the entire primary key (no partial
dependencies).

\textbf{Analysis of junction tables:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{title\_genre(tconst, genre\_id)} has a composite PK. There are
        no non-key attributes in this table, so 2NF is trivially satisfied.
  \item \texttt{principal(tconst, nconst, ordering)} has a composite PK. The
        attributes \texttt{category} and \texttt{job} describe the
        \emph{participation} (i.e., the combination of title + person + ordering
        position), not either entity alone. No partial dependency exists.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Conclusion:} All tables are in 2NF.

\subsection{Third Normal Form (3NF)}

A relation is in 3NF when it is in 2NF \emph{and} there are no \textit{transitive
dependencies} --- every non-key attribute must depend directly on the primary key,
not on another non-key attribute.

\textbf{Analysis:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item In \texttt{title}: \texttt{primaryTitle}, \texttt{originalTitle},
        \texttt{startYear}, \texttt{runtimeMinutes}, and \texttt{isAdult} all
        depend solely on \texttt{tconst}. No transitive dependency exists.
  \item In \texttt{rating}: \texttt{averageRating} and \texttt{numVotes} depend
        solely on \texttt{tconst}. Critically, \texttt{averageRating} does
        \emph{not} depend on \texttt{numVotes} (or vice versa) --- they are
        independent facts about the same entity.
  \item In \texttt{person}: \texttt{primaryName}, \texttt{birthYear}, and
        \texttt{primaryProfession} depend solely on \texttt{nconst}.
  \item In \texttt{genre}: \texttt{name} depends solely on \texttt{genre\_id}.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Conclusion:} The schema is in \textbf{3NF}. Further normalisation to BCNF
or 4NF is unnecessary as no overlapping candidate keys or multi-valued dependencies
exist in any of the six tables.

\subsection{Summary of Functional Dependencies}

\begin{align*}
  &\texttt{tconst} \rightarrow \{ \texttt{primaryTitle, originalTitle, startYear, runtimeMinutes, isAdult} \} \\
  &\texttt{tconst} \rightarrow \{ \texttt{averageRating, numVotes} \}                            \\
  &\texttt{genre\_id} \rightarrow \{ \texttt{name} \}                                             \\
  &\texttt{nconst} \rightarrow \{ \texttt{primaryName, birthYear, primaryProfession} \}           \\
  &(\texttt{tconst, genre\_id}) \rightarrow \emptyset \quad \text{(junction, no non-key attrs)}   \\
  &(\texttt{tconst, nconst, ordering}) \rightarrow \{ \texttt{category, job} \}
\end{align*}

% =============================================================================
\chapter{Stage 3: Creating the Database}
% =============================================================================

\section{Database Schema}

The database was implemented in MySQL 8 using the InnoDB storage engine, which
provides row-level locking, ACID compliance, and foreign key constraint enforcement.
The database is run locally using XAMPP (see Figure \ref{fig:mysql_setup}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{screenshots/mysql.png}
\caption{MySQL server running locally via XAMPP control panel.}
\label{fig:mysql_setup}
\end{figure}

The full \texttt{schema.sql} file (written entirely by me) is presented below:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle,
  caption={Complete database schema --- schema.sql (written personally by Ayaan)},
  label={lst:schema}]
-- ============================================================
-- CM3010 Database Coursework -- Schema
-- Dataset: IMDb Non-Commercial Dataset (movies 2000-2023)
-- Source: https://datasets.imdbws.com/
-- Author: Written personally by Ayaan
-- ============================================================

DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS imdb_coursework;
CREATE DATABASE imdb_coursework
  CHARACTER SET utf8mb4
  COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

USE imdb_coursework;

-- Table: title
-- Stores core metadata for each feature film.
CREATE TABLE title (
    tconst         VARCHAR(12)  NOT NULL,
    primaryTitle   VARCHAR(512) NOT NULL,
    originalTitle  VARCHAR(512) NOT NULL,
    startYear      SMALLINT     NOT NULL,
    runtimeMinutes SMALLINT     DEFAULT NULL,
    isAdult        TINYINT(1)   NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
    CONSTRAINT pk_title PRIMARY KEY (tconst)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

-- Index to speed up year-range queries (used in RQ3)
CREATE INDEX idx_title_startYear ON title (startYear);

-- Table: genre
-- Lookup table for genre names -- avoids repeating strings.
CREATE TABLE genre (
    genre_id  TINYINT UNSIGNED NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name      VARCHAR(64)      NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT pk_genre       PRIMARY KEY (genre_id),
    CONSTRAINT uq_genre_name  UNIQUE (name)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

-- Table: title_genre (junction / associative table)
-- Resolves the M:N relationship between title and genre.
CREATE TABLE title_genre (
    tconst    VARCHAR(12)      NOT NULL,
    genre_id  TINYINT UNSIGNED NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT pk_title_genre PRIMARY KEY (tconst, genre_id),
    CONSTRAINT fk_tg_title FOREIGN KEY (tconst)
        REFERENCES title(tconst) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE,
    CONSTRAINT fk_tg_genre FOREIGN KEY (genre_id)
        REFERENCES genre(genre_id) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

-- Index for fast genre-to-title lookups (RQ1, RQ4, RQ5)
CREATE INDEX idx_title_genre_genre ON title_genre (genre_id);

-- Table: rating
-- 1:1 with title -- separated to allow titles without ratings.
CREATE TABLE rating (
    tconst        VARCHAR(12)  NOT NULL,
    averageRating DECIMAL(3,1) NOT NULL,
    numVotes      INT UNSIGNED NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT pk_rating       PRIMARY KEY (tconst),
    CONSTRAINT fk_rating_title FOREIGN KEY (tconst)
        REFERENCES title(tconst) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

-- Index for rating-ordered queries (RQ1, RQ2)
CREATE INDEX idx_rating_avg ON rating (averageRating DESC);

-- Table: person
-- People who have worked on IMDb titles.
CREATE TABLE person (
    nconst             VARCHAR(12)  NOT NULL,
    primaryName        VARCHAR(256) NOT NULL,
    birthYear          SMALLINT     DEFAULT NULL,
    primaryProfession  VARCHAR(256) DEFAULT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT pk_person PRIMARY KEY (nconst)
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

CREATE INDEX idx_person_name ON person (primaryName(64));

-- Table: principal (junction / associative table)
-- Records who (person) did what (category/job) on which title.
CREATE TABLE principal (
    tconst    VARCHAR(12)  NOT NULL,
    nconst    VARCHAR(12)  NOT NULL,
    ordering  TINYINT      NOT NULL,
    category  VARCHAR(64)  NOT NULL,
    job       VARCHAR(256) DEFAULT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT pk_principal PRIMARY KEY (tconst, nconst, ordering),
    CONSTRAINT fk_principal_title FOREIGN KEY (tconst)
        REFERENCES title(tconst) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE,
    CONSTRAINT fk_principal_person FOREIGN KEY (nconst)
        REFERENCES person(nconst) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE
) ENGINE=InnoDB DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

CREATE INDEX idx_principal_nconst   ON principal (nconst);
CREATE INDEX idx_principal_category ON principal (category);
\end{lstlisting}

\section{Data Import Process}

\subsection{The Problem with Raw IMDb Data}

The raw IMDb files present several data quality challenges that must be resolved
before the data can be inserted into a relational database:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Null encoding:} All missing values are encoded as the literal
        string \texttt{\textbackslash{}N} rather than SQL \texttt{NULL}.
  \item \textbf{Multi-valued columns:} Genres are stored as comma-separated strings
        (e.g., \texttt{Comedy,Drama}) violating 1NF.
  \item \textbf{Scale:} The \texttt{title.principals.tsv} file alone contains over
        100 million rows; loading everything naively would overwhelm a local machine.
  \item \textbf{Referential integrity:} Person records must be inserted before
        principal records to satisfy foreign key constraints.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The Import Script --- \texttt{import.js}}

I wrote a custom Node.js data import script (\texttt{database/seed/import.js})
that addresses all four challenges. The script uses only Node.js built-in modules
for networking and decompression, plus the \texttt{mysql2} package for database
interaction. The key design decisions are:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Streaming:} Files are streamed directly from the IMDb HTTPS endpoint
        and piped through \texttt{zlib.createGunzip()} for decompression in memory,
        avoiding the need to store multi-hundred-megabyte files on disk.
  \item \textbf{Line-by-line parsing:} Node's built-in \texttt{readline} module
        processes the TSV one line at a time, keeping heap usage constant regardless
        of file size.
  \item \textbf{Batched inserts:} Rows are accumulated in memory and flushed to MySQL
        in batches of 500 using \texttt{INSERT IGNORE} to maximise throughput.
  \item \textbf{Null sanitisation:} A helper function \texttt{parseField()} converts
        every \texttt{\textbackslash{}N} value to JavaScript \texttt{null}, which
        \texttt{mysql2} transmits as SQL \texttt{NULL}.
  \item \textbf{Filtering:} Only rows where \texttt{titleType = 'movie'} and
        \texttt{startYear} is between 2000 and 2023 are retained. Principals are
        restricted to the four categories relevant to the research questions:
        \texttt{director}, \texttt{actor}, \texttt{actress}, and \texttt{writer}.
  \item \textbf{Referential safety:} The script builds in-memory sets of imported
        \texttt{tconst} and \texttt{nconst} values and filters out any principal
        record that references an entity not successfully inserted.
\end{itemize}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=jsstyle,
  caption={Key functions from import.js (written personally by Ayaan)},
  label={lst:import}]
'use strict';
const https    = require('https');
const zlib     = require('zlib');
const readline = require('readline');
const mysql    = require('mysql2/promise');

/** Convert IMDb's raw '\N' to null (written by Ayaan) */
function parseField(val) {
  return (val === '\\N' || val === '' || val == null) ? null : val;
}

/** Stream a gzipped TSV from a URL and process each row (written by Ayaan) */
function streamTSV(url, onRow) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    https.get(url, (res) => {
      const gunzip = zlib.createGunzip();
      const rl     = readline.createInterface({
        input: res.pipe(gunzip), crlfDelay: Infinity
      });
      let headerSkipped = false;
      rl.on('line', (line) => {
        if (!headerSkipped) { headerSkipped = true; return; }
        onRow(line.split('\t'));
      });
      rl.on('close', resolve);
      rl.on('error', reject);
    }).on('error', reject);
  });
}

/** Insert rows in batches for performance (written by Ayaan) */
async function batchInsert(conn, sql, rows, batchSize = 500) {
  let inserted = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < rows.length; i += batchSize) {
    await conn.query(sql, [rows.slice(i, i + batchSize)]);
    inserted += Math.min(batchSize, rows.length - i);
  }
  return inserted;
}
\end{lstlisting}

