\section{SQL Queries for Research Questions}

The five SQL queries below (written entirely by me) answer the research questions
defined in Stage 1. Each query was designed to avoid correlated sub-queries in
favour of efficient \texttt{JOIN} operations supported by the indexes defined in
the schema.

\subsection{RQ1: Top Genres by Average Rating}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle, caption={RQ1 --- Top genres by average IMDb rating}]
SELECT
    g.name                         AS genre,
    COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst)       AS total_movies,
    ROUND(AVG(r.averageRating), 2) AS avg_rating,
    SUM(r.numVotes)                AS total_votes
FROM genre       g
JOIN title_genre tg ON tg.genre_id = g.genre_id
JOIN title       t  ON t.tconst    = tg.tconst
JOIN rating      r  ON r.tconst    = t.tconst
GROUP BY g.genre_id, g.name
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst) >= 50   -- noise filter
ORDER BY avg_rating DESC;
\end{lstlisting}

\textbf{Design notes:} The \texttt{HAVING} clause filters out genres with fewer
than 50 rated movies, preventing genres with a handful of highly-rated arthouse
films from artificially topping the chart. This threshold is exposed as a
user-adjustable parameter in the web application.

\subsection{RQ2: Top Directors by Average Rating}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle, caption={RQ2 --- Top 10 directors by average film rating}]
SELECT
    p.nconst,
    p.primaryName                  AS director_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst)       AS films_directed,
    ROUND(AVG(r.averageRating), 2) AS avg_rating,
    MAX(r.averageRating)           AS highest_rated,
    MIN(r.averageRating)           AS lowest_rated
FROM person     p
JOIN principal  pr ON pr.nconst   = p.nconst
                   AND pr.category = 'director'
JOIN title      t  ON t.tconst    = pr.tconst
JOIN rating     r  ON r.tconst    = t.tconst
GROUP BY p.nconst, p.primaryName
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst) >= 5
ORDER BY avg_rating DESC
LIMIT 10;
\end{lstlisting}

\textbf{Design notes:} The \texttt{AND pr.category = 'director'} predicate on
the join condition (rather than in a \texttt{WHERE} clause) allows MySQL to use
the \texttt{idx\_principal\_category} composite index optimally. The minimum film
threshold of 5 prevents obscure directors from outranking prolific ones.

\subsection{RQ3: Average Rating Over Time}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle, caption={RQ3 --- Year-by-year average rating trend}]
SELECT
    t.startYear                    AS release_year,
    COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst)       AS total_movies,
    ROUND(AVG(r.averageRating), 2) AS avg_rating,
    ROUND(AVG(r.numVotes), 0)      AS avg_votes
FROM title  t
JOIN rating r ON r.tconst = t.tconst
WHERE t.startYear BETWEEN 2000 AND 2023
GROUP BY t.startYear
ORDER BY t.startYear ASC;
\end{lstlisting}

\textbf{Design notes:} Including \texttt{avg\_votes} alongside
\texttt{avg\_rating} is important for interpreting the trend: earlier years have
had more time to accumulate ratings, so a lower average vote count in recent
years may indicate underrepresentation rather than a genuine drop in quality.
This is visualised using a dual-axis Chart.js line chart in the application.

\subsection{RQ4: Runtime by Genre}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle, caption={RQ4 --- Average runtime in minutes by genre}]
SELECT
    g.name                          AS genre,
    COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst)        AS total_movies,
    ROUND(AVG(t.runtimeMinutes), 1) AS avg_runtime_minutes,
    MAX(t.runtimeMinutes)           AS longest_runtime,
    MIN(t.runtimeMinutes)           AS shortest_runtime
FROM genre       g
JOIN title_genre tg ON tg.genre_id = g.genre_id
JOIN title       t  ON t.tconst    = tg.tconst
WHERE t.runtimeMinutes IS NOT NULL
  AND t.runtimeMinutes BETWEEN 40 AND 360
GROUP BY g.genre_id, g.name
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst) >= 30
ORDER BY avg_runtime_minutes DESC;
\end{lstlisting}

\textbf{Design notes:} The \texttt{runtimeMinutes BETWEEN 40 AND 360} predicate
excludes statistical outliers: films under 40 minutes are generally short films
rather than features, and films over 360 minutes are rare exceptions (documentaries,
extended cuts) that would heavily skew the average.

\subsection{RQ5: Most Genre-Versatile Directors}

\begin{lstlisting}[style=sqlstyle, caption={RQ5 --- Directors by genre diversity}]
SELECT
    p.primaryName                        AS director_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT g.genre_id)           AS genre_count,
    COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst)             AS films_directed,
    GROUP_CONCAT(DISTINCT g.name
                 ORDER BY g.name
                 SEPARATOR ', ')         AS genres_worked_in,
    ROUND(AVG(r.averageRating), 2)       AS avg_rating
FROM person      p
JOIN principal   pr ON pr.nconst   = p.nconst
                    AND pr.category = 'director'
JOIN title       t  ON t.tconst    = pr.tconst
JOIN title_genre tg ON tg.tconst   = t.tconst
JOIN genre       g  ON g.genre_id  = tg.genre_id
LEFT JOIN rating r  ON r.tconst    = t.tconst
GROUP BY p.nconst, p.primaryName
HAVING COUNT(DISTINCT t.tconst) >= 3
ORDER BY genre_count DESC, films_directed DESC
LIMIT 20;
\end{lstlisting}

\textbf{Design notes:} A \texttt{LEFT JOIN} is used for the ratings table so that
directors with some unrated films are still included in the results --- their
overall versatility score remains valid even without a complete rating history.
\texttt{GROUP\_CONCAT} produces a readable, comma-separated list of genres for
display in the web application table.

\section{Reflection on Database Design}

\subsection{Design Decisions}

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Separating \texttt{rating} from \texttt{title}:} Keeping ratings
        in their own table with a 1:1 FK relationship means that unrated titles
        can exist in \texttt{title} without a placeholder row in \texttt{rating}.
        This is a cleaner representation of the real world than storing
        \texttt{NULL} rating columns directly in the \texttt{title} table.
  \item \textbf{\texttt{TINYINT UNSIGNED} for \texttt{genre\_id}:} Since IMDb
        defines only 26 genres, a \texttt{TINYINT} (max value 255) is
        perfectly sufficient and saves storage in the high-cardinality
        \texttt{title\_genre} junction table (480,704 rows).
  \item \textbf{Character set \texttt{utf8mb4}:} Movie titles include characters
        from dozens of writing systems. The \texttt{utf8mb4} encoding (unlike
        MySQL's legacy \texttt{utf8}) handles all Unicode code points, including
        emoji-like characters in some modern titles.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Challenges Encountered}

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Scale of \texttt{title.principals.tsv}:} At over 100 million
        rows, streaming this file without storing it to disk was essential.
        Attempting to load the full file into RAM would have exhausted system
        memory on a typical development machine.
  \item \textbf{Referential integrity ordering:} The Node.js import script must
        insert \texttt{person} rows before \texttt{principal} rows. Achieving
        this required collecting all needed \texttt{nconst} values during the
        principals stream, then importing names, then completing the principals
        insert --- a two-pass approach for those two tables.
\end{itemize}

