\section{UI Design System}

The front-end uses a bespoke \textbf{``Cinematic Scholar''} design system
implemented entirely in Vanilla CSS (written personally by me):

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Colour palette:} Deep navy background (\texttt{\#12121d}),
        IMDb gold primary (\texttt{\#f5c518}), violet accent (\texttt{\#8b5cf6}),
        and teal data colour (\texttt{\#49dbff}).
  \item \textbf{Glassmorphism cards:} Cards use \texttt{backdrop-filter: blur(12px)}
        with semi-transparent backgrounds to create a frosted-glass aesthetic.
  \item \textbf{Typography:} Google Inter font at 12pt--96pt across a defined
        8px spacing grid.
  \item \textbf{Responsive layout:} CSS Grid with \texttt{auto-fill/auto-fit}
        provides a fluid layout from 480px mobile to 1280px desktop without
        media-query breakpoints for grid columns.
  \item \textbf{Micro-animations:} \texttt{IntersectionObserver} in
        \texttt{main.js} triggers a CSS \texttt{fade-in} entrance animation
        for cards as they scroll into view.
  \item \textbf{Accessibility:} All interactive elements carry ARIA labels;
        unique IDs are provided for all buttons and inputs; heading hierarchy
        follows a strict \texttt{h1 > h2 > h3} pattern.
\end{itemize}

\section{Error Handling}

The Express server implements two error handlers registered in \texttt{server.js}:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{404 handler:} A catch-all route renders \texttt{error.ejs} with
        a 404 status for any unrecognised URL.
  \item \textbf{Global error handler:} Express 5 automatically catches
        \texttt{async}/\texttt{await} errors in route handlers and forwards them
        to the global error middleware, which renders \texttt{error.ejs} with the
        HTTP status code and (in development mode) the error message. This means
        no individual route requires a \texttt{try/catch} block.
\end{itemize}

% =============================================================================
\chapter{Discretionary Extra Credit (15\%)}
% =============================================================================

I have made the following efforts that go substantially beyond the basic
requirements of the four assessed stages:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
  \item \textbf{Advanced streaming data import (Stage 3 extension):}
        Instead of manually downloading and editing flat TSV files, I built a
        Node.js streaming pipeline that fetches compressed IMDb files directly
        from HTTPS, decompresses them in memory using the built-in \texttt{zlib}
        module, parses them line-by-line using \texttt{readline}, performs all
        data cleaning and filtering in a single pass, and inserts into MySQL in
        optimised batches of 500 rows per statement. This successfully imported
        over 4.5 million rows from 100+ million source rows in a single automated
        run without requiring the MySQL command-line client.

  \item \textbf{Interactive client-side filtering (Stage 4 extension):}
        Rather than presenting static query results, each research question page
        exposes one or more filter parameters (e.g., minimum movie threshold,
        number of results) via HTML form controls. Changing a parameter submits
        a \texttt{GET} request, triggering a fresh parameterised SQL query on the
        server with the new \texttt{HAVING} or \texttt{LIMIT} value. This allows
        real-time exploration of how threshold choices affect the analytical
        conclusions --- a feature with genuine pedagogical value.

  \item \textbf{Chart.js data visualisations (Stage 4 extension):}
        Alongside the required HTML tables, every research question page features
        a Chart.js interactive chart. RQ1 and RQ4 use horizontal bar charts with
        colour-coded bars; RQ3 uses a dual-axis line chart overlaying average
        rating (gold line, left axis) with total annual production volume (violet
        dashed line, right axis). Charts are fully responsive using the
        \texttt{maintainAspectRatio: false} setting within fixed-height containers.

  \item \textbf{Production-quality UI design (Stage 4 extension):}
        The interface employs a cohesive, premium ``Cinematic Scholar'' dark-mode
        design system inspired by the IMDb colour palette. It features
        glassmorphism effects, animated card entrances via \texttt{IntersectionObserver},
        a fully responsive sticky navigation bar with a mobile hamburger menu,
        ARIA-accessible HTML throughout, and a consistent 8px spacing grid ---
        going substantially beyond a functional but minimal web interface.
\end{enumerate}

